COMPETITION TIME! 💙🎁
In continuation and celebration of our beautiful ocean, we have partnered with @aquatech_imagingsolutions to host an ocean photo competition for a chance to win a $500 gift card from AquaTech!
To enter simply post one of your own original photographs that best represents what the ocean means to you. In the caption mention @Aquatech_imagingsolutions and @ocean plus use the hashtag #atoceancomp to have your photo enter the draw. The competition is open from ‪June 8-21‬, images can be captured on any device and multiple entries are accepted as long as posted from the 8th of June 2020. Our favourite images will have the chance to be featured on both AquaTech's and Ocean's Instagram pages with the final winner announced here ‪on June 24th.‬ Our winner will be chosen by a judging panel made up of ocean photographers @davesandford, @caitmiersphotography & @thurstonphoto.

For the full terms and conditions visit the link in our bio. #worldoceansday2020 #atoceancomp #aquatech
.
.
.
.This promotion is in no way sponsored, endorsed or administered by, or associated with Instagram.
.

We’ve joined with @sealegacy & @global_wildlife_conservation to share this unique and important perspective on the current state of our world.

#ExtinctionEndsHere

What comes after the Pandemic? This video message from the virus to humankind is a chilling reminder that our future is intimately connected with all other life on Earth. We know where the pandemic came from, and we know how to stop the next one. It's time to make our voices heard. Enough is enough. Now that our own vulnerability has been laid bare, it's time to demand #ExtinctionEndsHere -- for all life on Earth.

TAKE ACTION: ExtinctionEndsHere.org

Video: @SeaLegacy & @global_wildlife_conservation.

@shawnheinrichs @paulnicklen @mitty 💙

C’mon @dolphindronedom does it get any better than this!? 😍💙

node.text:
Repost and words from @thelifeofrileynz - “A heavy local line up. Stoked that sharks are more polite than they should be, given we have stripped most of the food out of the water and replaced it with us by the millions dressed to look like prey, splashing around in murky water at hunting time. Nothing against any other Apex predators, but I think it provides context to a sharks intelligence when you imagine doing the above scenario with a lion, tiger or bear. Or maybe all animals are just that much nicer than people. What do you think?”

Unknown filmer so DM for credit but I've seen these images so much more commonly these days from California and E Aus. The interesting question is will they continue to behave, what variables may influence adversity and how can we learn to co-exist and prevent luring apex predators into making mistakes. A tragic fatality happened yesterday in E Aus, likely from a very similar scenario to this. It's good to see there's non lethal policies starting to be implemented to help prevent such adversity. But still plenty of work to do. 🦈

“Do I have any dolphin stuck in my teeth?” 

To all the people that get in the water with Killer Whales around the world - you’re crazy. Look at those chompers! We spent yesterday afternoon with an outstandingly friendly pod of ETP (Eastern Tropical Pacific) Killer Whales a few miles off the coast of La Salina, Mexico. These whales REALLY enjoy hunting dolphins, playing with boats, and cruising the coastline. So much so, it’s the exact same thing they were doing when I first saw this pod in 2018. 

Taken aboard @pacificoffshore

A stunning capture of a Southern Right Whale and its calf amongst a bunch of surfers and a pod of dolphins by @trenny_m 💙

June to October is mating season for these whales, and after the calf is born (gestation period is about 1 year) it will grow quickly, doubling in size in 12 months. They can live to be a hundred years old!

Let’s work together to create an abundant and sustainable ocean where we can live in harmony with our ocean neighbours once more! 

#oceanimpact #southernrightwhale #planetocean
